******
[2] Finland, mink vaccine
Date: Sat 11 Dec 2021 [accessed]
Source: Finland's presentation, EC's PAFF Animal Health and Welfare committee meeting of 16 Nov 2021 [abridged, edited]
https://ec.europa.eu/food/system/files/2021-12/reg-com_ahw_20211116_mink-fin.pdf


[The following information is derived from the presentation, titled "Notification of a conditional usage permit for COVID-19 subunit vaccine (Furcovac) for minks."]

1. Notification of the Commission:
- Finnish Food Authority has granted on 22 Sep 2021 a conditional usage permit for COVID-19 subunit vaccine for minks for 46 500 vaccine doses (exp.d. 28 Dec 2021) to be used nationally
- The Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry of Finland notified the Commission on the conditional usage permit 23 Sep 2021
- The notification was based on regulation (EU) 2019/6 of the European Parliament and of the council on veterinary medicinal products and repealing Directive 2001/82/EC, which will apply from 28 Jan 2022.

2. Grounds for applying for a usage permit and the granting of a permit:
- Initiative for the vaccine development came from Finnish Fur Breeders' Association (FIFUR) and Helsinki University. The aim of the applicant is to protect breeding animals from SARS-CoV-19 infection. The process was based on the Medicines Act (395/1987), because so far, no COVID-19 vaccine for minks has a marketing authorisation in EU countries. Limited data requirements for quality, safety, and efficacy were agreed.

3. Conditions of the present usage permit:
- The applicant needs to provide more evidence about efficacy in the field before the possibility to continue the permit can be assessed.
- Also, vaccination does not allow mink farms to reduce the biosecurity measures.
- The use of vaccine does not alter the monitoring programme for infection of SARS CoV-2 in minks in Finland (based on CID (EU) 2021/788); so far, no infections in minks or other animals have been detected in Finland.
- The applicant intends to start vaccination early December [2021] after the end of the skinning season. If the usage permit is continued, the applicant aims to give the following vaccinations early 2022 well before the breeding season.

[Presented by Eero Rautiainen, Senior Veterinary Officer, Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry, Finland]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Finnish vaccine, developed by FIFUR and a team of scientists from the University of Helsinki, was named FurcoVac. The evidence about its efficacy in the field, required by the Veterinary Services before assessment of extending the vaccine's permit, is anticipated with interest.

COVID-19 has become, in fact, a "reverse zoonosis" (also known as zooanthroponosis and sometimes anthroponosis), referring to infectious diseases, the causal pathogens of which reservoired in humans while capable of being transmitted to non-human animals. Its mutants -- from human origin -- may cause re-infections in minks that had undergone earlier infection with the original Wuhan strain, or those that had been vaccinated with the 1st generation vaccines.

Researchers in Latvia were recently concerned that a sample of the virus from a Baltic Devon Mink enterprise was found to contain 3 significant mutations in the delta strain. This led them "to believe that a delta type might have been brought in and that a recombination had taken place." Such scenario could be envisaged with omicron and future mutants from human origin, as well as vice versa (see, in Latvian, at https://www.santa.lv/raksts/aktuali/ir-bazas-par-jaunu-covid-19-mutaciju-veidosanos-udelu-audzetava-46149/). - Mod.AS

